INSERT INTO analyses (id,kind,model,status,started_ts,finished_ts,input_tokens,output_tokens,cache_read_tokens,cache_write_tokens,cost_usd,question,report_md,tool_log_json,error) VALUES (1,'briefing','claude-haiku-4-5','done','2026-06-15T01:17:24.067255+00:00','2026-06-15T01:17:41.142301+00:00',10,1380,17315,16125,'0.028798',NULL,'## TL;DR
Portfolio shows weakness on short-term technicals (most holdings below SMA20) despite long-term strength — pullback likely in a bigger uptrend. **Hold; rebalance if SPY/broad market confirms reversal upward.**

## Portfolio
Up $274.95 today on $158k market value. MSFT is the only loser (-5.8% unrealized). NVDA ($30.7k, +69.6%), GOOGL ($21.6k, +102%), and AAPL ($23.3k, +33.5%) are the heaviest gainers. $34k cash on hand.

## Signals
- **Most concerning:** AAPL, AMZN, MSFT, NVDA all trading 3–7% below SMA20; AMZN (RSI 35) and MSFT (RSI 37) are oversold.
- **Bright spot:** JPM surged +$361.50 today (RSI 65 — overbought but still trending). SPY and VTI stable near SMA20 (RSI 53–54).
- **Drawdowns:** MSFT 34.2%, AMZN 21.7% from highs — consolidation or capitulation phase.
- **Contrast:** Long-term (SMA200) shows strength: GOOGL +16.8%, NVDA +8.4%, AAPL +9.1% — pullback within uptrend.

## Watch
- **ARM, MU on watchlist** both overbought (RSI 64, 61) with 100%+ moves vs SMA200 — tech rally momentum but at risk of reversal.
- **MSFT breakdown** — single loss in a green portfolio; if it breaks below current support, reassess.
- **Broad reversal confirmation:** If SPY/VTI bounce back above SMA20 with volume, current pullback is a buy; if they break below, shift to defensive.','[]',NULL);
INSERT INTO analyses (id,kind,model,status,started_ts,finished_ts,input_tokens,output_tokens,cache_read_tokens,cache_write_tokens,cost_usd,question,report_md,tool_log_json,error) VALUES (2,'weekly_review','claude-opus-4-8','done','2026-06-15T01:17:42.456531+00:00','2026-06-15T01:19:12.423379+00:00',13145,6877,40248,27465,'0.429430',NULL,'## Bottom line
You''re up **+25.2%** (time-weighted) but trailing the cash-flow-matched SPY benchmark at **+36.5%** — a **~11.4-point** gap. The single biggest cause is sitting on **17.7% cash** through a strong tape. The decision that matters most this week: deliberately deploy part of that cash, or consciously accept the drag.

## Do now
- **Put ~$12–15k of the $34k cash to work**, weighted to your broad sleeve (VTI/SPY) on the current 3–7% pullback below 20-day lines. Keep ~$18–20k dry.
- **Do NOT average down MSFT yet** — it''s below all three SMAs (−14% vs 200-day). Wait for a reclaim of the 50-day (~$412) before adding.
- **Add a starter to AMZN** (RSI 35, oversold, your smallest position) if deploying into single names.
- Leave the winners alone — GOOGL, NVDA, XOM need no action.

## Performance
- **Account value:** $192,465 (positions $158,430 + cash $34,035).
- **Unrealized P&L:** +$42,465 on $150k deposited.
- **Your return (TWR):** +25.19% vs **SPY +36.54%** over the same cash-flow window → **behind by ~11.4 pts.**
- **IRR (annualized):** +12.78%.
- **Cash drag is material:** 17.7% in cash while the benchmark compounded is the primary reason you lag SPY — not stock selection.

## Posture & risk
- **Cash:** $34,035 = **17.7% of equity** — high; the main lever on the SPY gap.
- **Concentration:** NVDA $30.8k (**16%**), top-3 NVDA/AAPL/GOOGL = **39%**, the five megacap-tech names ≈ **52%** of equity — and your SPY/VTI sleeve overlaps the same names.
- **Biggest structural risk:** megacap-tech / semiconductor concentration. A single AI-semis drawdown hits NVDA, the tech book, *and* your index ETFs simultaneously. That''s your one undiversified bet.

## Watch next
*(No web access this week — these are price/signal levels from the local data, not event-dated catalysts.)*
- **MSFT:** below all SMAs, −14% vs 200-day, RSI 37. Reclaim of the **50-day (~$412)** = repair signal; loss of **~$370** extends the downtrend.
- **JPM:** RSI **65** and above all SMAs — your hottest name. Watch for exhaustion; consider trimming if RSI pushes past 70.
- **NVDA:** mid-channel (RSI 45). Watch reclaim of the **20-day (~$215)** as the deploy/hold tell on your largest position.
- **Broad tape:** most holdings sit 3–7% under their 20-day — a mild pullback, not a break. Stabilization here is your cue to deploy cash.
- **Watchlist:** ARM/MU/AMD are stretched +100–157% over 200-day; **SMCI is broken** (−66% drawdown, below all SMAs). Don''t chase any of them.','[]',NULL);
INSERT INTO analyses (id,kind,model,status,started_ts,finished_ts,input_tokens,output_tokens,cache_read_tokens,cache_write_tokens,cost_usd,question,report_md,tool_log_json,error) VALUES (3,'market_brief','claude-haiku-4-5','done','2026-06-15T01:19:14.078067+00:00','2026-06-15T01:19:23.561757+00:00',10,781,17315,13869,'0.022983',NULL,'**Market posture: Risk-on with rising momentum fatigue.** Broad and tech indices are solidly above their 200-day moving averages (SPY +8.1%, QQQ +15.3%), with QQQ and small caps (IWM +14.1%) leading — classic risk-on positioning. However, RSI divergence is a warning flag: IWM and DIA are already at 60/59, approaching overbought, while all indices carry 9–12% drawdowns from recent highs. Near-term strength is real (QQQ +5.8% vs 50d), but the combination of elevated RSI in small caps plus meaningful pullbacks suggests momentum may be tiring.

**Watch: Small-cap relative strength.** If IWM rolls over while QQQ holds, that''s a risk-off signal. If both continue grinding higher despite RSI, the uptrend has more room. For now, treat this as "extended but not broken."','[]',NULL);
INSERT INTO analyses (id,kind,model,status,started_ts,finished_ts,input_tokens,output_tokens,cache_read_tokens,cache_write_tokens,cost_usd,question,report_md,tool_log_json,error) VALUES (4,'market_ideas','claude-opus-4-8','done','2026-06-15T01:19:26.369805+00:00','2026-06-15T01:19:47.432871+00:00',13143,1309,15366,9721,'0.166879','2','## AI & Semis watchlist screen

The screen splits the cohort cleanly: the parabolic names (ARM, MU, AMD) are stretched far above their 50-day lines and rank as trims/sells on extension risk, while SMCI is the opposite problem — a broken chart in a confirmed downtrend with a 66% drawdown. The constructive setups are the steadier compounders (AVGO on an uptrend dip, QCOM and TSM holding above both moving averages with neutral RSI). Note these are momentum/trend signals, not valuation or fundamental calls — position sizing should respect that AMD, MU and ARM can stay extended longer than expected.

**Portfolio context:** You already hold heavy semis beta via NVDA (~$30.8k, your largest position). Any new buy here adds correlation, so size additions modestly and treat the sells as watchlist names you''d simply avoid chasing rather than positions to exit.','[]',NULL);

